skills/humanizer — extended fork of blader/humanizer
  Upstream:          https://github.com/blader/humanizer
  Upstream license:  MIT, Copyright (c) 2025 Siqi Chen (see LICENSE-humanizer)

  The original work ("Part I": 29 patterns for detecting and removing signs of
  AI-generated writing, based on Wikipedia's "Signs of AI writing" guide) is
  retained in full. Per the MIT License, the original copyright and permission
  notice are preserved in LICENSE-humanizer.

  Modifications in this fork:
  - Added "Part II — Positive Human Patterns" (P1-P14): what to ADD to make
    writing read as genuinely human, not just which AI tics to remove.
  - Added human-factors-analysis.md: the analysis behind Part II, with verbatim
    excerpts from a calibration corpus of pre-LLM writing and a removal-to-
    addition cross-map.
  - Added a calibrated-confidence step, a positive pass, and a read-it-aloud
    (spoken-language) test to the process.
  - Integrated the skill as one renderer within Promptus; added a "ground" mode
    that cites and calibrates against the project knowledge store.

  Part II is derived from acclaimed writing published before large language
  models existed (1945-2015), across biology, computer science, mathematics,
  economics, statistics, psychology, and philosophy of mind. Sources are listed
  in human-factors-analysis.md and in the SKILL.md calibration corpus.
